msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1536
msgid "Start on the Connection tab: run Step 3 \"Check the endpoint is reachable\". If that fails, open Diagnostics on the same tab and confirm \"MCP adapter active and compatible\" and \"MCP REST endpoint registered\" both show green."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1537
msgid "The endpoint URL depends on your permalink mode. With pretty permalinks it is the /wp-json/ form; with plain permalinks it is the index.php?rest_route= form. Always copy whatever the Connection tab shows under \"Endpoint\" rather than typing it by hand:"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1539
#: includes/admin/page.php:1555
msgid "Pretty:"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1540
#: includes/admin/page.php:1556
msgid "Plain:"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1548
msgid "The client connects but the AI backend gets blocked (403 / 406 / 429)"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1550
msgid "This is the most common failure, and it is not an auth problem: the JSON-RPC POST never reaches WordPress at all. A CDN, WAF, or managed-host security rule sees automated traffic and rejects it before PHP runs, so you get a 403 (blocked), 406 (request looks like a bot), or 429 (rate limited) instead of a real MCP reply."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1551
msgid "Cloudflare:"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1551
msgid "turn off \"Block AI Bots\" / Bot Fight Mode for this site, and add a WAF skip (allow) rule for the MCP route so it is never challenged or blocked. If the site is behind Cloudflare Zero Trust / Access, exempt the route there too."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1552
msgid "ModSecurity / managed-host rules:"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1552
msgid "a generic rule returning 406 or 429 on POSTs from HTTP libraries is common on managed WordPress hosts. Ask the host to allow the MCP route, or add the path to the firewall allowlist."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1553
msgid "Add the allow / skip rule for whichever endpoint form your site uses (copy the exact one from the Connection tab):"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1558
msgid "To confirm it is the edge and not WordPress, run the curl probe below: if curl from your own machine gets a 200 but the AI client still fails, the block is on the proxy or IP path the AI backend uses, not on your endpoint."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1565
msgid "A page cache or CDN is intercepting the endpoint"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1567
msgid "Full-page caching (a caching plugin) or edge caching (the CDN) can serve a cached or empty response for the MCP route instead of letting the request hit PHP. The symptom is a stale, blank, or HTML response where JSON-RPC was expected."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1568
msgid "Exclude the MCP endpoint path from both full-page cache and edge cache. REST routes are dynamic and must never be cached:"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1570
msgid "(pretty permalinks)"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1571
msgid "(plain permalinks)"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1579
msgid "A redirect is breaking the request (trailing slash or http to https)"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1581
msgid "A 301 redirect — adding or removing a trailing slash, or forcing http to https — can drop the POST body or the Authorization header on the way through, so the request that finally reaches WordPress is empty or unauthenticated. This is the request not arriving intact, not a credentials problem."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1582
msgid "Use the exact endpoint URL the Connection tab shows, with the right scheme (https) and no extra trailing slash, so no redirect is triggered. If your server force-redirects http to https, make sure the config URL already starts with https so the POST is never redirected."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1589
msgid "Test the endpoint yourself with curl"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1591
msgid "This one-liner sends a real MCP \"initialize\" call to your endpoint with the agent user's Application Password. It tells you in one shot whether the endpoint is reachable, whether auth works, and — if it fails — which layer to blame. Replace the host, the username, and the Application Password (the password is the one shown once when you created it; keep its spaces):"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1593
msgid "If your permalinks are plain, use the index.php form instead:"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1595
msgid "How to read the result (the HTTP status on the first line):"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1597
msgid "200"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1597
msgid "reachable and authenticated; the body is a JSON-RPC result. Everything is working — if the AI client still fails, the block is on its side (see the 403/406/429 entry above)."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1598
msgid "401"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1598
msgid "reached WordPress but auth failed: wrong or expired Application Password, or the Authorization header is being stripped (see the Authentication section)."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1599
msgid "403 / 406 / 429"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1599
msgid "a WAF, CDN, or host security rule is blocking the request before WordPress (see the 403/406/429 entry above)."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1600
msgid "404"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1600
msgid "the route is not registered for this URL: flush permalinks (Settings → Permalinks → Save) and confirm you copied the endpoint exactly from the Connection tab."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1601
msgid "5xx"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1601
msgid "a server-side error: check your PHP error log and the host status."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1609
msgid "Windows: my client config won't start"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1611
msgid "Windows MCP clients cannot spawn the npx shim by its name alone. The launcher has to be wrapped so the command resolves:"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1612
msgid "You do not need to hand-edit anything — switch to the \"Windows\" tab in Connection → Step 2 and copy the config it generates. It already wraps the launcher correctly."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1619
msgid "My local or staging site won't connect (self-signed certificate)"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1621
msgid "Local stacks (DDEV, Local, Valet) serve a certificate Node does not trust, so the proxy refuses the TLS handshake. For local testing only, you can tell Node to accept it. The Connection tab already adds this for you when it detects a local site."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1622
msgid "Quick (least safe) — add this to the config env block:"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1624
msgid "Better — point Node at your local CA instead of disabling verification entirely (for example mkcert's rootCA.pem):"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1627
msgid "Never use any of these on a production site."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1634
msgid "Connecting a browser or OAuth client"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1636
msgid "There are two ways for an agent to authenticate. Most desktop clients use an Application Password: create one for the agent user under Users → Profile → Application Passwords, then paste the generated config from Connection → Step 2. Keep the password's spaces when you copy it."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1637
msgid "OAuth is the other way, and it is off by default. Turn it on under Settings and the agent connects by browser approval instead of a copied secret: you paste your site URL into the client and approve the request in your browser. The Connection tab shows the OAuth card and the endpoint to use once it is enabled."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1638
msgid "For browser-based clients, the plugin already exposes the session and approval headers a browser needs to read across origins (the MCP session id, the protocol version, and the OAuth challenge), so a web client can complete the handshake. If a browser client still cannot read the session header, check that nothing in front of WordPress is stripping CORS response headers."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1647
msgid "Authentication"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1651
msgid "The \"Authorization header reaches WordPress\" diagnostic fails"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1653
msgid "Some hosts and reverse proxies strip the Authorization header before it reaches PHP, so the Application Password never arrives and auth silently fails. Forward the header at the web-server layer."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1654
msgid "Apache (.htaccess) — either of these:"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1657
msgid "Nginx / FastCGI:"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1659
msgid "After applying, reload the web server and re-run Connection → Diagnostics."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1666
msgid "The Application Passwords option is missing from my profile"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1668
msgid "WordPress core only offers Application Passwords over a secure (https) connection. Behind a TLS-terminating proxy or load balancer, WordPress can see the request as plain HTTP even though the browser is on https — so it hides the option."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1669
msgid "Fix the proxy or HTTPS headers (or your site URL) so WordPress correctly detects https. Forwarding the standard X-Forwarded-Proto header from the proxy is the usual fix."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1670
msgid "Do not enable Application Passwords over genuine plaintext HTTP in production — the credential would travel unencrypted."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1679
msgid "Abilities & permissions"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1683
msgid "My agent sees fewer tools than I expected"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1685
msgid "This is intentional least-privilege behaviour. Each connection is filtered by the agent user's own capabilities, so the agent only ever sees abilities its role allows: reads need read capabilities; writes need the matching edit, publish, moderate, or manage capabilities."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1686
msgid "To expose more tools, grant the agent user the role or capabilities those abilities require. Granting more, of course, widens what the agent can do — keep it to what the agent genuinely needs."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1693
msgid "An ability is enabled but the agent still can't use it"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1695
msgid "Two things both have to be true for an ability to work:"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1697
msgid "The ability is turned ON on the Abilities tab. Everything is OFF by default."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1698
msgid "The agent user holds the WordPress capability that ability requires."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1700
msgid "If the toggle is on but the agent still gets refused, it is almost always the capability. Check the agent user's role."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1707
msgid "How the exposed and denied meta key lists work (and what * does)"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1709
msgid "Meta is locked down by default: until you list a key under \"Exposed meta keys\" on the Abilities tab, an agent cannot read or write any post meta. Two keys are always off limits no matter what you list: keys starting with an underscore (protected meta) and authentication keys. Those stay blocked even if you try to add them."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1710
msgid "A single * in the exposed list means \"allow every key except the ones that are blocked or denied\". The order the plugin checks is fixed: blocked keys lose first, then the denied list, then the exposed list (or the * wildcard). So the deny list always wins. A key in \"Denied meta keys\" stays hidden even when the exposed list is set to *."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1711
msgid "One thing to know about * and reading all of a post's meta at once: a single-key read works for any key * covers, but the \"read all meta\" ability only returns the keys you spelled out by name. Under a bare *, with no named keys, it returns an empty set. List the keys you want returned in bulk."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1718
msgid "Exposing term (category and tag) meta"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1720
msgid "Term meta has no field on the Abilities tab. It is off by default and you open it up with a small filter in your own code (a site-specific plugin or your theme's functions.php). Add the key names you want an agent to read or write on terms:"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1722
msgid "The same protections apply as for post meta: underscore-prefixed and authentication keys are stripped out even if your filter tries to add them."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1729
msgid "My custom post type is not available to the agent"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1731
msgid "Out of the box an agent can only touch posts and pages. Every other content type is off until you turn it on under \"Exposed content types\" on the Abilities tab. Only public, non-internal types show up there to choose from."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1732
msgid "If you would rather set this in code, the same list runs through a filter you can add to:"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1734
msgid "After exposing a type, the agent still needs the WordPress capabilities for that type, and the relevant abilities still have to be turned on."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1743
msgid "Clients, privacy & limits"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1747
msgid "Which AI clients work, and how do I set each one up?"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1749
msgid "Claude Desktop, Claude Code, Cursor, and Windsurf all connect the same way: through the @automattic/mcp-wordpress-remote proxy, which is the package the Connection tab puts in the generated config. The proxy reads your endpoint URL and the agent user's Application Password and builds the auth itself."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1751
msgid "Claude Desktop:"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1751
msgid "paste the generated block into its claude_desktop_config.json (Settings → Developer → Edit Config) and restart the app."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1752
msgid "Claude Code:"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1752
msgid "add the same server to its MCP config (claude mcp add, or the .mcp.json in your project)."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1753
msgid "Cursor:"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1753
msgid "add the block to its MCP config (~/.cursor/mcp.json, or Settings → MCP) and reload."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1754
msgid "Windsurf:"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1754
msgid "add it under its MCP / plugins config (mcp_config.json) and refresh the server list."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1756
msgid "Copy the config straight from Connection → Step 2 — do not hand-build it. On Windows, use that tab's \"Windows\" view (it wraps the launcher in cmd /c); for a local or staging site, it adds the certificate handling. Both are covered in the Connecting section above."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1757
msgid "The hosted ChatGPT and Gemini apps cannot connect in this release."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1757
msgid "Their web connectors expect a native streamable HTTP/SSE MCP transport, which the bundled adapter does not serve yet, so they cannot reach the proxy the way the clients above do. Gemini CLI is the exception: it runs as a proxy client, like Claude Code, so it works today, and the Connection tab has a ready-made quickstart for it."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1764
msgid "What can and can't this plugin do? (the security model in plain language)"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1766
msgid "The plugin is built to be safe by default. In plain terms:"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1768
msgid "No external calls."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1768
msgid "It never phones home. Your credentials and your content never leave the site — the AI client connects in to you, not the other way round."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1769
msgid "A dedicated low-privilege user."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1769
msgid "The agent authenticates as its own separate WordPress user via an Application Password — not as you, and not as an administrator. You choose that user's role, so you set its ceiling."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1770
msgid "Two locks on every ability."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1770
msgid "An ability works only if you explicitly enabled it on the Abilities tab AND the agent user's capabilities allow it. The default is nothing enabled — the agent starts with zero abilities until you turn them on."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1771
msgid "Deletes are trash, not destroy."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1771
msgid "Delete-style abilities move content to the Trash, where you can restore it; they do not permanently erase it."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1772
msgid "Everything is logged, values are not."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1772
msgid "Every call — including denied ones — is recorded on the Activity Log tab with the argument KEYS only, never the values. You can see what was attempted without leaking what was in it."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1773
msgid "Optional extra guardrails."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1773
msgid "The Settings tab adds a per-minute rate limit, an IP allowlist, a force-to-draft switch, and a maximum title length. All four are off by default, so you turn on only the ones you want."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1781
msgid "What does the plugin log, and does it call out to anything?"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1783
msgid "The plugin makes no external calls — nothing about your site or its content is sent anywhere."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1784
msgid "The activity log records only the argument KEYS of each call (never the values) plus the source IP address of the request. You can clear it any time from the Activity Log tab."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1791
msgid "Is there rate limiting?"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1793
msgid "Yes. The Settings tab has a \"Rate limit (per minute)\" field. Set it to a number and each connection can make at most that many agent calls per minute; set it to 0 to turn the limit off. The cap is counted per agent user, so two connections do not eat into each other's budget."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/page.php:1794
msgid "Calls that go over the limit are denied, and each denial is written to the Activity Log like any other blocked call, so you can see when a connection is hitting the ceiling."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/settings.php:206
msgid "Plugin reset. Every setting and the activity log were cleared; your agent user and its content were left alone."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/settings.php:227
msgid "These safety controls are optional. They all start off, and the plugin runs fine without any of them. Turn on only what you need."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/settings.php:240
msgid "Rate limit"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/settings.php:241
msgid "Per minute"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/settings.php:246
msgid "How many agent calls one connection can make per minute. Set it to 0 to leave the limit off."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/settings.php:254
msgid "Before you save a list with anything in it, add the IP address your AI client connects from. As soon as this list has one entry, any request from an address that is not on it is blocked, including your own agent. Get it wrong and every agent call stops."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/settings.php:259
msgid "IP allowlist"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/settings.php:260
msgid "One per line"
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/settings.php:264
msgid "One IP address or CIDR range per line. Leave it empty to allow connections from anywhere. When you save, any line that is not a valid IP or range is dropped."
msgstr ""

#: includes/admin/settings.php:272
